A blanket implementation is a trait implementation for all types matching a trait bound, rather than for a specific type. It uses generics in the impl block.

Classic example from the standard library:

impl<T: Display> ToString for T {
    fn to_string(&self) -> String {
        format!("{}", self)
    }
}

This means every type that implements Display automatically gets ToString for free. You never need to implement ToString manually.

Other examples:
- impl<T> From<T> for T -- every type can be converted from itself
- impl<T: Into<U>> From<T> for U -- the Into/From duality
- impl<T: Error> From<T> for Box<dyn Error> -- any error can become a boxed error

The orphan rule states: you can implement a trait for a type only if either the trait or the type is defined in your crate. This prevents conflicting implementations across crates.

You CANNOT do: impl Display for Vec<T> (both Display and Vec are from external crates).

Workarounds:
1. Newtype pattern: struct MyVec(Vec<i32>); impl Display for MyVec { ... }
2. Create your own trait: trait MyDisplay { ... } impl MyDisplay for Vec<T> { ... }
3. Extension trait: trait VecExt { fn my_method(&self); } impl VecExt for Vec<T> { ... }

The newtype pattern is the most common and idiomatic solution.

Sized is an auto-trait meaning 'this type has a known size at compile time.' Almost all types are Sized. Generic type parameters have an implicit T: Sized bound.

?Sized (pronounced 'maybe sized') relaxes this bound, allowing dynamically-sized types (DSTs) like str, [T], and dyn Trait.

DSTs can only exist behind a pointer: &str, &[T], Box<dyn Trait>. These are 'fat pointers' carrying both a data pointer and size/vtable metadata.

Using ?Sized is necessary when writing generic code that should work with both sized and unsized types:

fn print_it<T: Display + ?Sized>(value: &T) {
    println!("{}", value);
}
// Works with both &String (Sized) and &str (unsized)
